node.text:
McLaren Special Operations today unveils the ‘Albert’ Speedtail, a bespoke commission by @mclarenbeverlyhills. ‘Albert’ is an homage to the first Speedtail attribute testing prototype from 2018 with one of the most complex paint themes ever completed by MSO. ​

The exterior design reflects the aerodynamic prowess of the McLaren Speedtail with beautifully painted lines representing the optimised airflow over the car. ​

#McLaren #Speedtail #MSO

node.text:

node.text:

Together they deliver a power to weight ratio of 598PS per tonne at dry weight. The experience of this force unleashed will leave a deep impression.​
​
#McLaren765LT #McLaren765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by McLaren Automotive on August 13, 2021. May be an image of car and road.

node.text:
The pursuit of lightness is the pursuit of greatness. The 765LT Spider is defined by ruthless, exhaustive weight saving. Like every Longtail before it. The results are felt on every straight. In every corner. The figures speak volumes. This car is 80kg lighter than the lithe,720S Spider. And has a class-leading power-to-weight ratio.​
​
#McLaren765LT #McLaren765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren

node.text:
Complementing the 765LT ‘Longtail’ coupe unveiled last year – all of which are sold – the new 765LT Spider is McLaren’s most powerful-ever convertible supercar and brings highest-ever levels of driver engagement to the McLaren LT experience​.
​
#McLaren765LT #McLaren765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by McLaren Automotive on August 12, 2021. May be an image of car and outdoors.

node.text:
The convertible roof design plays an integral role in the structure, featuring a carbon fibre frame within the Retractable Hard Top panel and creating a full carbon fibre shell when closed. There are also additional comfort benefits for occupants – because it is a single-piece panel with no central seal, headroom is improved, while the extended length of the roof panel allows the tops of the A-pillars to be further forward, enhancing the sense of space and easing ingress and egress.​
​
#McLaren765LT #McLaren765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by McLaren Automotive on August 11, 2021. May be an image of car.

node.text:
Our smallest LT, the 600LT, does without an active spoiler. Here, a fixed wing more akin to a fully-fledged racer sits proudly on the rear deck. As well as helping the car generate 100kgs of downforce at 155mph, it neatly frames the 600LT’s flame spitting rear deck-mounted exhaust pipes. It’s a good thing its centre portion has a heat resistant coating to keep it scorch free. 

#McLarenEvolution

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by McLaren Automotive on August 11, 2021. May be an image of car.

node.text:
At the time, the P1 was our most technologically advanced car, so its spoiler was never going to be a simple affair. Like the MP4-12C, it was active, but it borrowed from Formula One with DRS (Drag Reduction System) technology adjusting the spoiler’s angle of attack for improved performance. It could sit flush with the car, raise five inches on the road, or up to twelve on track to provide the optimum experience for drivers.

#McLarenEvolution

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by McLaren Automotive on August 11, 2021. May be an image of car.

node.text:
The first new generation McLaren came with an active spoiler that, at a glance, looked perfectly integrated in to its aerodynamically efficient body. While the MP4-12C’s spoiler could indeed sit snug in the car’s body for high speed running, it could also pop up to aid downforce and reduce lift, or it could be used as an air brake to slow the drivers down. 

#McLarenEvolution

The 765LT Spider's stunning design focal point is the convertible roof, playing an integral role in the structure, featuring a carbon fibre frame within the Retractable Hard Top panel and creating a full carbon fibre shell when closed.​

​

#McLaren765LT #McLaren765LTSpider #Supercar #McLaren

The exacting development of the RHT and the fact the chassis doesn’t need any stiffening ensure that the Spider is in every respect a true driver’s car – extremely track-focused and dynamically the equal of the coupe.”​

James Warner, Chief Engineer, McLaren Automotive​
